title: This is the R5 1600 12nm refresh!
content: The original R5 1600 release in 2017 was the 14nm process. This is a refresh based on the Zen+ 12nm process, aka the 2xxx series. This processor can be Oc'd quite well and will perfrom on par with a 2600/x depending on OC. This is a steal for this price/performance ratio.//Update: I've been running at 4Ghz for the last week with no issues, this is amazing price/perf ratio
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 13, 2019

title: As confirmed by others, this is the 12nm refresh of the R5 1600, and well worth it!
content: The good:  12nm refresh of the R5 1600.  A little confusing at first, as I hadn't heard about any such thing, only on researching the part number (YD1600BBAFBOX... note the F in the 4th to last character rather than E), did I eventually find information about this (along with another reviewer's posting here)The bad: not even really that bad, but, considering that this revision of the CPU is closer to being a slightly lower-clocked 2600, versus an original 14nm version of the 1600, it comes with the Wraith Stealth cooler (as does the 2600), rather than the Wraith Spire.  Just a little puzzling at first, and a minor nitpick, as the Stealth is easily adequate for this CPUs needs.I've only had it installed for a few days now, but am very happy with it - an excellent deal for a better-than-expected processor.

title: This is not exactly a 1600 and isn't quite a 2600, but it is a 6 core Ryzen plus ...
content: This is a 2nd generation Ryzen plus CPU sold in a box indicating it is a first generation Ryzen CPU. It uses the Ryzen Plus 12 nm chipset and identifies as Pinnacle Ridge (which is Ryzen Plus). Mine varies in speed between 2900 and 3600 Mhz. It is likely this will vary by customer, case and random chance with respect to how good the silicon the CPU really is.It appears AMD is selling these as they may not qualify for sale as Ryzen 2600's due to clock issues (they clock a bit slower more or less). They do clock faster than 1600's. Overall for $85 at this time (early 2020) this is the most powerful CPU at this price point ( under $100).If you want a place holder, or just a decent Ryzen Plus at an amazingly good price this is a good purchase. It  will not outperform a Ryzen 3, or even a Ryzen Plus 2600. It will nearly match a Ryzen Plus 2600 though. This CPU, $50 for RAM and $80 for a motherboard, and you can have a Ryzen Plus upgrade for $215. This isn't intended to overclock much, you may get it to overclock a little. For moderate needs, this is a wonderful product.

title: It's truly a 2nd gen Zen+ 12nm part. Code named "Pinnacle Ridge" under CPUz.
content: Update Feb 14th : I just bought two more of these and pairing them with Amazon Warehouse Tomahawk B450 boards($76 a piece). I decided to sell my old Sandybridge cpu/board/ram and would even upgrade my kids hand me down PC's to these as the price isn't that much considering I get about $80-100 for each of my old hardware setups. What those systems do overclocked with more watts and temps, this does effortlessly stock , cool and quiet. I am a bang for the buck shopper with 7 PC's around the house , so these 1600AF can someday replace my Intel Dual core setups.I recently upgraded my Sandybridge 8yr old 4.7ghz i7 with a 2700x for $136 after cash back from Amazon card(Thanks Tech Deals youtube channel). I liked the upgrade so much that I also wanted a similar feel for 1 of my MediaPC's that I run a GTX970 in. Figured this 1600AF would likely be a great value for a budget HD/4k TV gaming setup. I just finished installing it and I ran a benchmark on my 2700x and then dropped in the 1600AF all stock settings with 3200mhz C16. Without changing a thing except CPU, both runs showed my GTX1070 is 99% GPU bound under "The Shadow of the Tomb Raider" benchmark. I know lower detail would help show performance differences in the CPU but for my quick test I am very pleased with the performance at stock. No difference than my 2700x. Max temp is 34c with a Noctua 14 cooler. I will soon move this 1600AF CPU/MB/RAM over to the Media PC case with Prism RGB cooler from my 2700x purchase.(update it's running great as the MediaPC, cool,quiet and smooth) Loving this value. Check out my attached screenshots of afterburner CPU utilization and benchmark results. Hope this helps someone!
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 3, 2020

title: 1600 AF is the CPU Value King!
content: Like a lot of others have said, this is the AF version of this CPU, which means a 12nm node with Zen+ updates. This is basically an underclocked Ryzen 5 2600. Gamer's Nexus did a really good YouTube video on this CPU if you are interested in the more technical details.My personal experience is using this with an ASUS Strix B450-F Gaming motherboard and a Fractal Design Celsius S24 AIO cooler. This booted no problem with my motherboard. After doing some initial stress tests to make sure it was stable and everything was working ok, I went back to the BIOS to overclock it.Also, I should note that I did not do a fresh install of my OS after swapping CPUs. I run Windows 10 with whatever the current update is as of Jan 2020. On intial boot, my WiFi was disabled, but I had already loaded the chipset drivers onto a USB drive. I installed the chipset driver, rebooted, and everything was more or less back to normal. I did show all my hidden devices in Device Manager, then went through and removed everything related to my old CPU and old Motherboard. Not really sure that was needed, but it's what I did. Windows did not seem to mind at all, and it is still showing up as activated.I was able to hit 4.0 GHz pretty easily. All I did was change the multiplier from Auto to 40, and TPU from Auto to TPU II. Rebooted and stress tested again, rock solid at 4.0 GHz with occasional single core boosts to 4.4 GHz and multi core boosts to 4.2 GHz. Note that I did not use PBO or really anything else to do this.Temperatures while testing never went above 50c. The interesting part about that is my AIO has a hardware based auto mode that seems to throttle the fans independently of the motherboard. The fans never really seemed to ramp up to maintain the 50c temperature.One other thing I wanted to note was a comparison to my old processor, an Intel 4790k running at stock speeds. I lost the silicon lottery with that CPU, and it would never really OC past 4.4 GHz without running up the voltage quite a bit, to the point where the CPU was running very hot. However, it would undervolt pretty well while running at stock speeds, so I just ran it undervolted for about 5 years. Setup like this, it would run at around 70-77c with the same cooler, and the fans were working much harder.The R5 1600AF runs most of my games with a few more frames at the top end and average (maybe 5-10 depending on the game). However, my low frames and perceived smoothness is night and day. I am easily gaining 10-30 frames on the low end. The desktop also feels a lot snappier.So overall, I am happy. While I didn't gain an amazing FPS boost, my PC is much quieter and my experience is much better. If I did any actual productivity work, I would probably notice even more of a difference. For $85, I am thrilled with this processor. Easily the best CPU I have ever purchased.
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 6, 2019

title: Got practically a 2600x with an overclock
content: Best chip at this price point, totally leveling the competition(even internally) . These chip are 12nm dies, and perform right below at 2600. With an overclock you easily can raise clocks to 2600 levels, and a lot of people are getting 4-4.1ghz in the 1.3v range, though there are still some that canonly do 3.8-3.9 so don't expect that from all. Seems like at least some of these batches are valid 6 core dies binned straight to the 1600, instead of being dies that didn't make the 2600 bins cut. Lot of variance, which you really don't see with most amd. Many of these chips could of made the bin for 2600/2600x it seems.Even at stock these chips are a great buy, but for enthusiast or anyone wanting to take some time to overclock they really shine even more price wise. Hearkens back to the days when you were able to overclock and get the performance of a better chip that was x2 the price.Mine does 4.1ghz @ 1.325v 3533mem(1.175vSoc)  can also do 4.2 @ 1.38-1.39
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 9, 2020

title: The best value CPU on the USA market.
content: I know not every country has this CPU, but if yours does I say snatch one up. It's 12 nm and at stock uses less power than a regular 1600 and the 2600. Overclocked a lot of these CPUs can match a 2600X. I recommend this CPU for office PCs, productivity tasks and gaming. If you're looking for a cheap 1080p gaming rig pair this with a RX 570 4gb and you're set without hitting any CPU bottlenecks, if you're doing 4K gaming use the difference you save on this CPU and buy a RX 5700 XT(at 4K you're mostly going to be GPU bottlenecked), but if you're looking for super fast productivity results and/or high refresh FPS gaming in my opinion this isn't the CPU for you.Paired with a B450 motherboard and a RX 570 4gb your have a bargain PC :).

title: Ryzen 5 1600 AF!
content: This is the updated version of the Ryzen 5 1600, absolutely the best value you can get (right now)! This is my 5th ryzen cpu, I've owned the following: Ryzen 5 1400, Ryzen 3 2200G, Ryzen 7 1700X, Ryzen 5 3600 (my favorite), and this Ryzen 5 1600.  I bought it to replace the Ryzen 3 2200G that I was temporarily using in my Living Room / VR mini PC and it's absolutely perfect.  It performs on par with the Ryzen 5 2600 since it uses the updated architecture, but only costs $85 (at launch)!I've paired it with a GTX 1070, 16 GB RAM, and using the stock cooler it runs all the VR that I throw at it in VR quite well - and yes, it can handle Half Life: Alyx :)  I'd recommend this cpu for gaming above any other unless you can afford the jump to the Ryzen 5 3600.  If you are building a bang-for-your-buck system, this 5 1600 AF is absolutely perfect.

title: Great CPU
content: Great little CPU. I usually use my laptop for the majority of the time, and running a R5 in that I decided to upgrade the home PC to this century. I went from an A10 series with DDR3 to this and a new Mobo with DDR4 for a total cost of $280 and the difference is night and day. Benchmark scores went from being in the top 80 percentile to top 10 for this year and generally this series Ryzen appears somewhere between the 7th gen i7s and the current gen i5's and as of now (6/20) two years after manufacture, the Ryzen 5 1600 STILL sits at #7 for best processor for power and price. As a bonus I found it mated well with all the components within the system and handles a moderate OC of 3.8Ghz @ standard voltage 24/7. I am going to build another system based off of the Ryzen line and give this one to my son as AMD has proven it's salt recently and I can't wait to give the thread rippers a go. Great job AMD

title: This is hands down a SOLID bargain chip for EVERYONE!
content: Honestly I am just floored with how much I love this CPU! My PC just feels snappy, it runs everything I throw at it. I can't believe that I have 6 cores and 12 threads in a BUDGET gaming PC! I'm only running it stock so the Wraith Stealth cooler it comes with is more than sufficient. It stays under 45c most of the time, and 65-75c while gaming. I have played some major titles such as Shadow of the Tomb Raider, Star Wars the Fallen Order, and a few others and it really stays cool. I've also tested HEVC videos and they play flawless, which surprisingly is something my old i7 4770k couldn't do. Plus this processor is only 65 watts which is practically half the power of that 4770k which I had overclocked.I just can't say it enough, I'm VERY happy with this processor! Great job AMD!
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 14, 2020

title: The orphan CPU. Great if you can get it at a good price.
content: This is such a unique CPU. Technically a first generation Ryzen but it has second generation features. It's a limited edition "orphan".A refresh of Ryzen 2600 (some say 1600). AMD had run out of 14 nm wafers so they used the newer 12 nm ones to build these. It doesn't show up on most QVL CPU lists for Ryzen type motherboards but it's so generic that it seems to run on any of them, without a bios update. I installed this on a MSI B450 Tomahawk MB and it fired right up. 6 cores and 12 threads, its base clock speed is 3.2 GHz but my motherboard throttles it up to 3.6 GHz. Comes with a decent CPU fan (no LED lights) so this doesn't run hot at all. Seems to be a good combo with DD4 3200 MHz ram. Great for 3D creation programs like Blender and most AAA games if you add a good graphics card.Also, it's very low power at 65 watts.I was lucky to get this at the $85 release price which was an incredible deal. YouTube went crazy reviewing this when it first came out. It sells for almost twice as much now as of this writing (May 2020). It's not a good deal at this current price. You could almost get a Ryzen 3600 (3rd generation and 7 nm) for the price now.This beats my old AMD 3850 8 core CPU (125 watts) in performance.I'm going to swap in a 12 core / 24 thread 3900 in a year or so when that price goes down to $200. But this is quick enough for me until then.
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 25, 2020

Have not had any issues getting all the Security patches either. It's a winner.

title: Very impressive processor
content: This was my first AMD build and I decided to choose this cpu.  I overclocked it to 4 ghz and am using a noctua u9s with dual fans to cool it.  It's completely stable at 4ghz and max temps are around 69 degrees when running prime 95 and it stabilizes around that temperature.  I am using a gigabyte b450m ds3h motherboard and an Intel 7600p nvme m2 to run windows on and 16gb of oloy 3000mhz ram.  My gpu is a sapphire nitro 8gb RX570 and my psu is a 600 watt EVGA. I am blown away by the price to performance from this pinnacle ridge Ryzen 5 1600.

title: A significant performance bump from the AE Sku
content: I build quite a few computers every year just for fun as a hobby, and last year was the year of the cheap Ryzen 5 1600AE, the original 14 nanometer process Zen 1 6 core 12 thread processor.This, though, is the AE Sku which just alludes to 12 nanometer picasso architecture.While this chip is very similar to the Ryzen 5 2600, it is actually a 1600 that has just been miniaturized. it has architectural differences from the 2600.That being said, the performance out of the box is smack between the 1600AE and 2600 in multi core, and closer to the 2600 in single thread.this chip didnt seem to have any issues at 4.1GHz - 1.4V all core. At that point, it's basically identical performance wise to the 2600.Worth noting, this also comes with the larger Wraith spire cooler, however mine had an all aluminum cooler, not the copper slug version shipped with the 1600AE. the 2600 ships with a stealth, so this is a lot better in my opinion there.Highly recommended at $80, and even $105... but not more than that. get the 4600.

title: An absolute steal for a budget gamer.
content: TLDR: This chip is the perfect upgrade for anyone who built a sub-$400 budget gaming PC with an AM4-based AMD Athlon processor - the performance difference is night-and-day.This version of the R5 1600 offers performance similar to the 2600 for $40 less. If you followed one of those "$300-400 budget rig" build guides on Youtube from a couple years ago that used the AM4 Athlon chips, this is an absolute no-brainer. It works on 300-series boards without the need for a BIOS update, which is very handy given it's effectively a Zen+ architecture CPU in everything but name.The included cooler, while not as beefy as the original AE variant chips, still does a great job keeping this chip cool under load at stock clock speeds. Paired with a GTX 1650 Super, this particular SKU of the 1600 outperformed the Athlon X4 950 by up to 3x the framerate in most games. The difference in synthetic benchmarks were also very impressive for a now sub-$100 chip. (See images)I know I've already stated this multiple times, but it really does need to be said; If you're still using an Athlon X4 9xx or 200GE, now is the time to upgrade, and this is the chip you should  be upgrading to.
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 18, 2020

title: Absolute best price / performance on the market short of the R5 3600
content: I am a huge fan of this AF variant of the 1600. I can confirm this product listing is for the 12nm refresh, running under a Hyper 212 LED vertical push/pull (I have a 1st revision AM4 support model with incorrect slats) and running Crossfire 2x 570 4gb's (unrelated: don't do this, it's not for the feint of heart and very much out of support after Radeon driver 20.1.2).One concern I would have is possible motherboard support- I did purchase an MSI B450-A Pro MAX that did support it out of the box but I have heard anecdotally that it *theoretically* may not play nice with certain motherboards out of the box due to it listing as a 1000 series part but internally it is 2000 series. Very old BIOS revisions of other mobo's may not post or error out attempting to get to OS?Performance is fantastic out of the box, boosts up to 3.7GHz, and stays there, when ram is set to A-XMP (16gb 2933MHz dual channel CL16 here) and during all core sustained settles at 3.45GHz with barely any heat. Mine benches somewhere between the R5 1600X and the R5 2600.Currently with the 1600AF being sold in the USA for $85 and the R5 3600 being on sale regularly for $175 gaming has never been cheaper with CPUs. If you have the budget spring for the 3600 however I am 100% happy long term with the 1600AF. Room to upgrade but I likely won't need to for a long time.
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2020

title: Amazing cpu for reasonable price.
content: I understand that it is a common practice but the installation instructions provided are general directions that have the installation process for all the different versions of Ryzen processors instead of just the one that is in the box. This could lead to confusion if someone isn't careful which set of instructions they start following and they could end up damaging they're motherboard or cpu. Years ago I had a fm2 system and ordered an fm2+ cpu to upgrade, I went through two Amazon replacements before I realized that I was ordering the wrong type of cpu. Point is the exchange and return policy was very helpful and convinient. Basically, as long as you order the correct cpu for your system and follow the correct instructions for your cpu, installation will be quick and easy.  Though I've read that this cpu was priced lower previously (as low as $85) I purchased it at $104 and I believe that the $19 difference is well worth it my last system had an integrated A6 5200 Apu and was painfully slow for around $300 (cpu $104, motherboard $70, 16 gb ram $70, 120 gb ssd $25, 600 w PSU $50 free shipping) my system is about 300% faster. Using an old GeForce gt 710 GPU I can even do some lightweight gaming until I upgrade to a more modern card for AAA titles.

title: An excellent CPU for the Price NOTE! it is $85 not $150
content: Excellent CPU when "AMD Reseller" has it in stock. They sell it for $85.PLEASE DO NOT BUY IT FROM A THIRD PARTY SELLLER! title: The value/performance king of the 2020 CPU market
content: This is a 12nm refresh of the original 2017 AMD Ryzen 5 1600, or you can call it a slightly underclocked 2600. In case I need more performance I can easily upgrade to 3rd-4th gen Ryzen as they sit on same AM4 socket.It's stock cooler (Wraith Stealth) is decent enough to keep the CPU temperature in 70s under heavy load. I would consider upgrading it though for overclocking or for using in hotter environments.All in all, it's a superb product for the price. For comparison, Ryzen 5 3600 cost (at the time I purchased this item for $85) $175 while it's only 30-40% faster at best. And it's not even worth buying 2600 for $120 or more. There was no direct competitor in Intel area as well, their i3 9100F is almost twice slower in multi-core optimized tasks. So grab this CPU if you find it under $90.

title: Insanely good value, old first gen boards may need a bios update.
content: The performance per dollar is insane. 6 core 12 thread cpus would have been $200+ just a few years ago. So finding it for under $100 is amazing. I am using in what is effectively a home office PC, and it is rather overkill. The performance gain over the 1500x and 1200 for the money is a no brainer. Choosing between this and a 3200G/3400G APU is a tougher decision that comes down if you have an old dGPU laying around( Since i had an old R9 270 not being used for anything else so the choice of the 1600 over an APU was easy enough), and if the APU's graphics chip can really push enough pixels for your uses case. (for an office pc the APU probably would have be sufficient.) The included cooler is not ideal, but works well enough. I had a spare Wraith spire LED cooler from the RMA of my 1700 (seq fault issue with early ryzens), and it kept it under 60 C (with the fans set to 50%) while running Prime95 for over an hour. From what i can see the included cooler runs more in the mid 70 C range. If you can find a wraith spire led or similar for cheap it is definitely worth the upgrade over the included stock cooler (wraith stealth) assuming space is not an issue.Running this in a super low end mother board will limit the boosting somewhat. You will want to look for boards with an 8 pin rather than 4 pin cpu power connector, and the B450 or X470 chipset. This is a zen+ 12nm part so earlier boards like B350, and X370 may need a bios update to work this this processor despite the first gen part naming chosen by AMD.
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 2, 2019

title: MUST BUY
content: (EDIT10/06/2020) it has now been well over 6 months time and ive since upgraded my gpu to a 2070s ftw 3 ultra+ and an ek D-RGB 240mm aio, with  a 144hz view sonic freesync monitor (gsync works) and when figuring out that spread spectrum can help with over clocks well, i turned it off and got my vcore down to 1.235 volts on a x570 gaming wifi edge mb. needless to say im still very happy with this purchase, debating on getting new ryzen when it comes out or just staying where i am...While under full FULL LOAD mine at 4.1ghz @1.28V never hits above for 20 min stress testing on all core with occt stresstest its at 56c.... got to 4.1 merely by bumping to 1.28volts nothing else tried booted first try. Going to tinker more but anyhow...Nothing I dislike traded my zotac amp gtx 1060 6gb gpu for one of these brand new. The guy bought it from this seller. For 85.00 now they raised the price but still well worth. Had a 2400g but more then enough for an upgrade.edit, sad you can no longer get these from the seller that offered a great deal on them in fact no longer available is sad af... but still i got one and am dam happy over this vs my 2400g clocked @ 3.9 @ 1.38volts hit some temps with the aio but yea thankk you amd authed reseller and the guy i traded with.EDIT: since trading or purchase of this cpu ive obtained some WAY better ram, a new case and 5700 to boot with 2tb nvme, and a few other goodies. i have people telling me the r5 1600 AF isnt able to do 3466 ram. so i put some pics in. yea i didnt post stress test pics but i give my word (old backwoods ky boys word) that 8 hours of aida 64 stressing everything but the gpu and drives its stable after that! specs are MSI b450I gaming plus ac, of course this cpu, 4.1ghz @ 1.33 volts LLC4, 16gb 2x8 hyper X 3466 cas 16 ram, 240ml aio, and well thats all you need to know the ram kit i have for this is ( copy this and search amazon) ! HyperX Fury 16GB 3466MHz DDR4 CL16 DIMM (Kit of 2) 1Rx8  Black XMP Desktop Memory HX434C16FB3K2/16 kit, anyhow the ram works on xmp profile 1 or 2. thanks reseller! probably going to snag another here really soon and throw my old tower back together with a new mb that supports 4 dimms and see my luck!

title: Great Value CPU & experience with 3rd party seller!
content: Likes -* value, purchased at same price as an Intel I3 9100F from a third party on Amazon at $85.00, 4 chores/4 thread (Intel) vs 6 core/6 thread (AMD) - actually been an Intel fan since they generally have had better single core performance but with the multicore performance being a bigger factor these days, I went with AMD* package arrived early & good condition* with my RAM running at 3200mhz, it boosts to 3.7ghz while gaming or under heavy load (it's rated boost clock is 3.6 but the BIOS adjusts the CPU frequency automatically when A-XMP is enabled), drops to 3.2 or lower during general web browsing or productivity tasks* while gaming, it stays around 10% to 20% usage while my GPU is close to 100% (RX 570 8gb), my Intel I3 4160 was at 100% in the same situation and cost twice as much when purchased in 2016* mine came with the Wraith Stealth instead of the Spire cooler which does the job though I won't be overclocking until it's replaced with an aftermarket solution - Cooler Master Hyper 212 Black Edition or ARCTIC Freezer eSports DUO for example* on overclocking, back in the 90's & early 00's you could see a noticeable impact in real-world situations, now it seems to impact synthetic bench marks primarily so I don't see a need for it in my case though I'll probably give it a go just for the experience at some point in the near future
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 23, 2020

title: CPU is a beast for the price
content: Update, this is now the 2nd one I have bought for a build. They are amazing. Successfully overclocked to 3.95 with memory clock at 1500MHz. Pairee it with a Tomahawk B450 MOBO and oloy ddr4 3200 RAM, overclocked to 3350. I have now had a total of 5 VMs open at one time and this thing just does not care. Buying a third for one more build, but will continue buying these guys.This CPU is amazing, at the time of writing this review I have 3 VMs running, GNS3 running, installing Red Hat Linux, chrome obviously open and Vuze running. The CPU is sitting at 34 percent utilization. The CPU sits at around 40 - 50 Celsius with included fan, which is also great. I did not get that much on the overclock, mostly due to motherboard. Was able to overclock to 3.85 with a voltage of 3.5. When put in a stress test still sits between 70 and 80 Celsius. Have played many AAA titles with it and it works just fine, games like Shadow of the Tomb Raider, all of the Need for Speeds and The Witcher are on high / ultra-high settings. With this CPU I am using an XFX RX580 graphics card. This CPU makes more a great CPU at a cheap price for a cheap gaming / work computer.
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 29, 2020
